Single-database configuration for Flask.

See ``MIGRATIONS.md`` for the complete command and deployment runbook.

Schema lifecycle
----------------

Alembic migrations are the only supported way to create or change the database
schema. Application startup intentionally does not call ``db.create_all()``.

New empty database
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

From the ``backend`` directory, with ``DATABASE_URL`` configured for the target
database, run::

    flask --app app:create_app db upgrade

Existing database that already matches the baseline
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Do not run the baseline upgrade over existing tables. First take a database
backup and verify that its tables, columns, constraints, and indexes match the
baseline revision. Then record the baseline without executing its DDL::

    flask --app app:create_app db stamp 20260621_base_schema

After the database has been stamped, future revisions can be applied normally
with ``flask --app app:create_app db upgrade``.

Never stamp a database merely to bypass a failed migration. A stamp asserts
that the target database already has exactly the schema represented by that
revision.
